<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B3EFFBCFF088C30FDCD6725" blockId="73.[151,530,1049,1075]" box="[151,530,1049,1075]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<heading id="F11281E62B3EFFBCFF088C30FDCD6725" bold="true" box="[151,530,1049,1075]" fontSize="11" level="1" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" reason="1">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B3EFFBCFF088C30FDCD6725" bold="true" box="[151,530,1049,1075]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
Genus 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B3EFFBCFF718C30FDCD6725" authority="Schultze, 1878" authorityName="Schultze" authorityYear="1878" box="[238,530,1049,1075]" class="Demospongiae" family="Darwinellidae" genus="Aplysilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dendroceratida" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B3EFFBCFF718C30FE876725" bold="true" box="[238,344,1049,1075]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Aplysilla</emphasis>
Schultze, 1878
</taxonomicName>
</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AA5A368A2B3EFFBCFF088C76FDE767D6" blockId="73.[151,1436,1119,1216]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B3EFFBCFF088C76FEC9676E" bold="true" box="[151,278,1119,1144]" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Definition.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B3EFFBCFE808C76FE61676E" authorityName="Merejkowsky" authorityYear="1879" box="[287,446,1119,1144]" class="Demospongiae" family="Darwinellidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dendroceratida" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Porifera" rank="family">Darwinellidae</taxonomicName>
in which the sponge body is always encrusting and the skeleton is composed only of fibres, which are clear of detritus and typically, unbranched (
<figureCitation id="32DE2A0F2B3EFFBCFCDA8CADFC7F678A" box="[837,928,1156,1181]" captionStart="FIGURE 2" captionStartId="9.[151,250,1811,1833]" captionTargetBox="[150,1436,193,1790]" captionTargetId="figure@9.[150,1436,193,1790]" captionTargetPageId="9" captionText="FIGURE 2. Plakortis pulvillus sp. nov. A. Preserved sample; B &amp; C. Skeletal architecture (B, x5; C, x 10); D. Diods." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/2651452/files/figure.png" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">Fig. 2A</figureCitation>
). In some species, for example 
<taxonomicName id="6DE54D092B3EFFBCFA9B8CADFEE867D6" authority="de Laubenfels" authorityName="de Laubenfels" class="Demospongiae" family="Darwinellidae" genus="Aplysilla" kingdom="Animalia" order="Dendroceratida" pageId="73" pageNumber="74" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="polyraphis">
<emphasis id="9891EA982B3EFFBCFA9B8CADFA43678B" box="[1284,1436,1156,1181]" italics="true" pageId="73" pageNumber="74">A. polyraphis</emphasis>
de Laubenfels
</taxonomicName>
, branching is frequent.
</paragraph>
